The paper deals with revenue maximization in auctions, which is a classic topic in game theory and mechanism design. The use of LP and primal-dual analysis suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. The consideration of both Bayesian and Dominant-Strategy implementations suggests that the paper also belongs to the cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category, which deals with the design of algorithms and protocols for distributed systems. The use of virtual value functions and quasi-linear utilities suggests that the paper also belongs to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category, which deals with the design of intelligent agents and decision-making systems. The focus on revenue maximization suggests that the paper also belongs to the cs.EC (Economics and Computation) sub-category, which deals with the intersection of computer science and economics. Finally, the use of primal-dual analysis and LP suggests that the paper also belongs to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, which deals with the design of algorithms and models for learning from data.
